				\begin{document}$${{{{{{\bf{w}}}}}}}^{{{{{{\bf{T}}}}}}}=\frac{{{{{{\bf{h}}}}}}{{{{{{\bf{C}}}}}}}^{-{{{{{\bf{1}}}}}}}}{{{{{{\bf{h}}}}}}{{{{{{\bf{C}}}}}}}^{-{{{{{\bf{1}}}}}}}{{{{{\bf{b}}}}}}}$$\end{document}</tex-math><mml:math id="M78"><mml:msup><mml:mrow><mml:mi mathvariant="bold">w</mml:mi></mml:mrow><mml:mrow><mml:mi mathvariant="bold">T</mml:mi></mml:mrow></mml:msup><mml:mo>=</mml:mo><mml:mfrac><mml:mrow><mml:mi mathvariant="bold">h</mml:mi><mml:msup><mml:mrow><mml:mi mathvariant="bold">C</mml:mi></mml:mrow><mml:mrow><mml:mo>−</mml:mo><mml:mi mathvariant="bold">1</mml:mi></mml:mrow></mml:msup></mml:mrow><mml:mrow><mml:mi mathvariant="bold">h</mml:mi><mml:msup><mml:mrow><mml:mi mathvariant="bold">C</mml:mi></mml:mrow><mml:mrow><mml:mo>−</mml:mo><mml:mi mathvariant="bold">1</mml:mi></mml:mrow></mml:msup><mml:mi mathvariant="bold">b</mml:mi></mml:mrow></mml:mfrac></mml:math><graphic xlink:href="41467_2022_35328_Article_Equ8.gif" position="anchor"/></alternatives></disp-formula></p>
      <p id="Par59">A nice feature of (7) is that <bold>h</bold> only affect power but not <italic>α</italic>. In practice, <bold>h</bold> can be estimated using the summary statistics from GWAS (details see estimation of <bold>h</bold> section). It can be shown that (5) is a special case of (7) when <bold>δ</bold> is same across all GWAS,<disp-formula id="Equ9"><label>8</label><alternatives><tex-math id="M79">\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
